		<body>
			<pb n="1R"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Pottsville</placeName> <date>October 13<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1851</date>.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">Dear Sir&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)">Your very excellent letter in<lb/> answer to my note of inquiry of last <date>Monday</date>&#44; was received in<lb/> the latter part of the week.  And I am unable sufficiently to<lb/> thank you for your kindness and promptness in furnishing<lb/> me an answer.  On the subject referred to&#44; it is all that I<lb/> could desire&#44; and has satisfied my mind on a point which gave<lb/> me some perplexity&#44; and in regard to which I was unable to obtain<lb/> any satisfactory information.  Nothing would give me greater<lb/> pleasure than a personal acquaintance with you&#44; and the priv&#45;<lb/>&#45;iledge of hearing you converse on matters which have always<lb/> been deeply interesting to me&#44; and which are common to both<lb/> systems of religion&#44; to which we respectfully adhere.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I am thankful&#44; also&#44; for the information you give with<lb/> reference to the works mentioned in your letter.  I will be<lb/> pleased to purchase them.  And as I will be in the city about<lb/> the first of <date>November</date>&#44; I will embrace the opportunity you<lb/> kindly offer&#44; and will call on you in order to obtain them.<lb/> From what you say of them&#44; it appears that they are just<lb/> the books I want.  In order that you may know<lb/> something about me&#44; &#40;not for the purpose of laying any claim<lb/> to a title&#44;&#41; I will state that I am a minster of the Asso&#45;<lb/>ciate Reformed Presbyterian Church&#8212;the same denomina&#45;</p>
			<pb n="1V"/>
				<p>tion with which <persName>Rev. I. B. Dales</persName> of <placeName>Philad.</placeName> is connected&#59;<lb/> with whom&#44; perhaps&#44; you are acquainted.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">The misnomer by which I addressed you in the direc&#45;<lb/>tion of my letter&#44; you will please attribute to my ignorance<lb/> of your present position.  I knew that you were once the<lb/> &#8220;minister of the <placeName>Cherry St.</placeName> Synagogue.&#8221; and had the pleasure<lb/> of being present once&#44; when you officiated&#58; but I was not<lb/> aware that <add>your connection with that</add> congregation had been dissolved&#44; at least in a<lb/> ministerial capacity.  Such difficulties will happen to the<lb/> best of men.  Said I have generally discovered that congrega&#45;<lb/>tions acting in that manner&#44; eventually find to their own<lb/> chagrin&#44; that in maltreating their minister&#44; they have been<lb/> &#8220;kicking against the pricks&#8221;&#8212;hurting themselves more than<lb/> him.  I will be glad to have a letter from you again&#44;<lb/> and at any time you may find it convenient to write</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">With great regard</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">Yours &#38;c&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)"><hi rend="underline"><persName role="author">D. J. Caruahan</persName></hi></p>
		</body>
